{{expansion}}
One who is '''right-handed''' is more dextrous with one's [[Left and right|right]] [[hand]] than with one's [[Left and right|left]] hand: one will write with their right hand, and probably also use this hand for tasks such as personal care, cooking, and so on. According to different studies, 85% to 90%<ref>Pyschology for A-level ''second edition, page 309''</ref> of the [[population]] is right-handed, while most of the remaining are [[left-handed]]. A very small percentage of the population can use both hands equally well; a person with this ability is deemed to be [[ambidextrous]].

==Meanings of the word "right"==

The English word ''right'' can refer to<ref> The New Oxford Dictionary of English</ref>

* Morally good or acceptable
* True or correct as a fact (also ''adverb'' correctly)
* To restore a normal or upright position
* A moral or legal entitlement to something
* Of or relating to conservative political views
* On the right-side of the body

A person may also describe somebody as his [[right hand man]], which means that he relies heavily on this person, deriving from the importance and superiority place on the right over the left by many civilizations.


==="Right" in other languages===

* The French word ''droit'' can refer to the right-side of the body. It can also refer to the study of law or to ''rights'', an entitlement to something<ref>[http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Droit Wikipedia.fr (in French)]</ref>.

* The Latin word ''dexter'' means right and as with the English word dextrous, can refer to skill or skilfullness.

==Why is the population right-hand dominant?==

It is not known with any degree of certainty why the population is right-hand dominant. 

According to scientific theory, the right-side of the body is controlled by the left hemisphere of the brain, and visa-versa. In right-handed people, the left hemisphere of the brain is the dominant hemisphere<ref>Pyschology for A-level ''second edition, page 309''</ref>.

A recent study <ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/4242419.stm BBC website]</ref> found that right-handers use the right-side of the brain to focus on a entire image, but the left-side of the brain to focus on details within an image.

==Theories explaining right-hand dominance==

====The warrior and his shield====

This theory attempts to explain why right-handedness is more common by the position of a warrior's shield and his heart. Since the [[heart]] is on the left side of the body, a right-handed warrior (who holds his shield with his left hand to free the right hand for a weapon) would be better able to protect his heart and therefore more likely to survive in combat.


==Right-handedness in society==

In the past, many schools around the world forced left handed children to write right-handed<ref>[http://www.sciam.com/askexpert_question.cfm?articleID=00063C8D-61EF-1C72-9EB7809EC588F2D7 Scientific American website]</ref>. A good number of technological devices are made primarily for right-handers, examples of everyday objects primarily designed for right-handers include refrigerators, scissor, can-openers and padded kitchen mittens (padded on one side only). Musical instruments such as guitars are also set up for right-handers. Military rifles designed to be shot from the right shoulder only have resulted in injuries from spent cartridge casings hitting [[left-handed|left-handers]] in the eye and head{{fact}}.

Being right-handed does not always mean that the favored foot is also on the right side. When playing soccer for instance, many people prefer using their left foot rather than the right, despite being right-handed<ref>[http://toddlerstoday.com/resources/articles/lefthand.htm Toddler Today website]</ref>

Some doctors say it starts in the pregnancy stage when the baby sucks either its left or right thumb at its 24th day{{fact}}.

